Strong Consistency - synchronized, locks
Guarantee: after a write, every read sees the latest value.
    Synchronous replication
    Leader-based systems
    Locking / coordination

Eventual Consistency - async updates, queues
Guarantee: if no new updates happen, all replicas will eventually converge.
    Caches
    Distributed databases (like Dynamo-style)
    Microservices with async communication


Idempotency
Running it multiple times produces the same result as running it once.
Solves -> duplicate effects

One way to guarantee idempotency is to use keys.
    - Request sends idempotency keys and server store it.
    - If the operation where to be a success validates the keys


What can we do to improve user experience:
Typical architecture
    Write → goes to primary DB (strong-ish consistency)
    Read → from replicas/cache (eventual consistency)
    Communication → async (queues, events)

Silly example:

class PaymentProcessor {
    private Set<String> processed = ConcurrentHashMap.newKeySet();

    public void process(Payment p) {
        if (processed.contains(p.id)) return;

        // process payment
        processed.add(p.id);
    }
}